[8281354]

A2 Nils Carlsson is the prominent scientist on their team. While the crew in general were working to build the Magellan Project, Nils and a few others were secretly researching and trying to find ways to reverse the Mush infection. Ian came to help, and Stephen pretended to be helping before they found out he was a fake. Finola refused to come because she wouldn't leave the miners, but she did share her research with them. Of course Chun also participated, since most of the cure attempts were based off her unique biology.

In the end, Nils became too sick to travel with them, so Paola took his place in the crew.

Q10 If an object is dropped in a room does it automatically go into a shelf or do I need to click on the shelf to open its inven' then drop the item?
On june 2, 2014
[8281354]

A9 If it's better than a fruit that one of your potted plants produces, you can graft it onto that plant - make sure that everything is fully watered, healthy and clean, both you and the plant! This will give you a mature plant faster than waiting for a planted version of that fruit to show up, and means you don't have to wait for a plant to die so you can have the pot back.

If you are short on pots and have inactive crew members, plenty of the traders seem to favor trades where you can obtain more pots. You're only limited by how much AP your botanists have.

If you have no more pots and all your plants are as good as or better than the fruit in question, it is just fine to eat them. Remember that freezing them will extend the time they are safe to eat and, as mentioned earlier, that Janice has first dibs on morale fruit since she can't gain it as easily as anyone else.

SummerMcLovin

A50: Too much work for me to bother with anything serious about distributions etc. (four years at uni with Stats was enough), but I've seen lots and lots of misses on my ships and heard of some getting it very easily.

Will go through each room and list the probabilities of best possible steps in order. The best will be bold; other routes in italics, unwanted ones normal or unspecified. You can go to the alternate room's listing and multiply the fractions for whatever route the RNG gives you instead.

Front Turrets: 1/2 for Front Corridor; 1/2 for Bridge
Bridge: 1/3 for Front Corridor; 2/3 for Front Turret
Front Corridor: 1/8 for Front Storage; 1/8 for others
Laboratory: 1/2 for Front Corridor; 1/2 for Medlab
Medlab: 1/3 for Front Storage; 1/3 for Lab; 1/3 for Centre Bravo Turret
Hydroponic Garden: 1/2 for Front Storage; 1/2 for Front Corridor
Centre Bravo Turret: 1/2 for Bravo Bay; 1/2 for Medlab
Centre Alpha Turret: 1/2 for Front Storage; 1/2 for Alpha Bay
Central Corridor: 1/4 for Alpha Bay; 1/4 for Bravo Bay; 1/4 for Front Corridor; 1/4 for Refectory
Refectory: Certainty of Central Corridor
Bravo Bay: 1/5 for Centre Bravo Storage; 1/5 for others
Alpha Bay: 1/4 for Centre Alpha Storage; 1/4 for others
Rear Corridor: 1/4 for either Rear Storage; 1/8 for Alpha Bay; 1/8 for Bravo Bay; 1/8 for others
Nexus: Certainty of Rear Corridor
Bravo Dorm: 1/2 for Rear Corridor; 1/2 for Bravo Bay
Alpha Dorm: 1/2 for Rear Corridor; 1/2 for Alpha Bay
Engine Room: 1/3 for either Rear Storage; 1/6 for others
Icarus Bay: 1/3 for Engine Room; 1/3 for Rear Corridor; 1/3 for Rear Bravo Turret
Alpha Bay 2: 1/4 for Engine Room; 1/4 for Rear Corridor; 1/4 for Alpha Bay; 1/4 for Rear Alpha Turret
Rear Bravo Turret: 1/2 for Engine Room; 1/2 for Icarus Bay
Rear Alpha Turret: 1/2 for Engine Room; 1/2 for Alpha Bay 2

So overall, you hope that people go inactive in the rear of the ship. The Engine Room and Rear Corridor are not too hard (compared to the usually brutal RNG difficulty); Alpha Bay (and thus Dorm) is better than their Bravo counterparts; trying to get to Front Storage from anywhere that has to go through Front Corridor is a bitch.

[6826491]

This is more of an Ask the SDF question, but I'll answer it here anyway. The logs are only for the eyes of the SDF judges, mods, and MT staff, so you'd have to be one of those to actually be allowed to see them, sorry. I will admit that it's fascinating to read some of these reports at times, and I've felt that way about them since I was a judge.

I can say that we have access to the timeline of everything that happened on the ship: When and where actions were taken, all conversations, and all private messages. Judges can't see any usernames of those on the ship, but mods can and do see them. (The mods have to see them, in order to effectively do our jobs!) After judges rule on reports, they're gone from that judge's queue, and they no longer have access that particular set of logs. Mods can pull up previous reports after they've been ruled on, for the same reason we can see usernames; how else would we be able to deal with appeals?

However...after a certain period of time (the length of which will never get disclosed publicly) ship logs automatically get purged from the system. The reports themselves, as well as the verdicts involved do remain, but the logs themselves are gone. So you can't read logs from months ago, because they quite literally no longer exist.

Peanutz
Mais pourquoi est-il aussi mchant ?

They don't attack immediately. If they appear at the beginning of cycle 4, they will attack at the beginning of cycle 6. Asteroids collide with the Daedalus after 6 cycles.

If hunters appear after the ship moves, they attack at the end of that same cycle (hunters appearing at the beginning of cycle 4 after moving will attack at the beginning of cycle 5). Asteroids will collide in 5 cycles.

If you move the ship when there are hunters, the different types of enemy ships behave differently :
- aracks prevent the ship from moving
- trax follow the ship (they are still visible while it moves)
- asteroids and D1000 never follow
- regular hunters reappear when the ship stops, but only 50% of them (or 25% if you have the project Trail Minimizer).

A120: It's not against the rules, per se. But it's not something I can reasonably recommend either, specifically because it may inadvertently lead to people on other ships getting killed. Some ships end up having similar circumstances, and paranoid people tend to act without sufficient information...if the circumstances seem to fit closely enough, innocent people may get killed as a result of your post. It's happened before. Whether or not people should use what they read on the forum to figure out who the Mush may be, it's akin to spoiler you can't unsee; once it's out there, you have no control over who reads it, nor how they may react to it.

Though it's also fair to say that in some cases, a genuine request for advice leads to the requester giving themselves away, and/or their partner. Case in point: Here. This is a very good example of how not to ask for advice, and I'm sure it was a lesson brutally learned.

After the thread I linked got posted, it's fair to assume that those two characters got some extra scrutiny on multiple ships, at least until the thread creator had posted enough info to pinpoint exactly which ship he was on. It's human nature to read into things like that, though. In light of that, I'm going to agree with goat on this one, and say it's kind of a dick move to do that. Again, the consequences to other ships could be problematic...so I'll ask you to not do it, regardless of whether it might break any rules (and it wouldn't, but I've stated why it would be a bad idea.)

Peanutz
Mais pourquoi est-il aussi mchant ?

Wait for the right occasion, and in the meantime, make yourself useful and trusted. Waiting will allow you to watch the crew, know their weak points, find what targets will hurt most (it can be morale, or hunters, or Pilgred, depending on who is inactive and what skills are missing). After a few days, the crew can get both more imprudent (they might start staying in camera-free rooms, for example) and more nervous, which means that if you have done your job and stayed clean, they might start killing other people, who have been dirty or done odd things.

Expeditions can also be great opportunities. You can go down to Icarus bay, get dirty and wash, to spike someone if the room isn't protected, or if you stay on board and they haven't secured the hacker kit, you can abandon the expedition team.

A191 - Most of the time, humans killing humans is not a reportable offense, because there is a reason for it. They were acting suspicious, or a title needed to be passed on; the morale hit and the loss of a useful team member is enough to make sure that random murderings is kept to a minimum.

Reportable killings are ones done for no reason at all. They said something mean to you in chat. They took your bed or won't give you one. You think they're a bad player or too inexperienced to do well. They refused to take a random food test and you have no other reason to suspect them. You're a griefer just trying to make things "interesting". See the difference?

b - This question is a little hard to read. I think you are saying that you are human on a ship where people are about to start dying because of no oxygen, and you have a suspicion but don't want to get reported for random killing?

At any rate, if you are putting facts together and marking people as suspicious, you probably won't get reported if you were mistaken. You killed them because you thought they were a mush. If the majority of your ship is against killing this person, or the mush all appear to be dead and nothing suspicious has been going on, that would be playing against your team, which is reportable; however most ships don't have the luxury of time to get a total crew vote before killing. If you're in doubt and afraid you'll get reported, open a private chat to somebody and lay out your reasons for the kill.

"Once your appetite goes..." is for the most consumables eaten.
"Energy Dissipator", probably the most AP spent on 'pointless actions' such as wandering around, failing to hit things with Turrets etc.
"Super Optimizer" is the opposite of the above, least AP 'wasted'.
"Two left hands" is the most failed attempts at repairs.
"Anonymous Hacker" for most successful uses of the Hacker Kit.
"Pointless Player" for the most AP spent solving the MAD Kube, even if they succeeded.
"Brute Force Mutant" is the opposite of Violence is Evil for a Mush player, the most damage dealt or kills racked up I'd guess.
" I shouldn't have come " is for getting lost on an expedition, whoever has the most if there were more than one.

On july 6, 2014
Kyubey

A223
Melee base damage 1-3, 60% to hit, 2-4 with Solid, 3-5 with Wrestler
Knife: 1-5, 60% to hit, skills give no bonuses
Blaster: 2-3, 50% to hit

But there is one important thing - if you attack with your fists there is no risk to make yourself an injury, and no chance to make an instant-kill and no chance to make a dangerous injury to target.
Things are totally different with knife and blaster - while you get chance to deal with your enemy with one attack or make him unable to fight back or do bonus damage with injuries, you only put yourself on risk - you can make an injury to self.
Shooter gives you double chance to make critical hits, and lowers the chances to get in trouble by 50% as well. Blaster is useful for not-shooter, if you need to deal with target asap and you are ready to risk, but better to leave it for a professional, if he is online and ready, he will do much better.
Blaster is also useful to kill targets in heavy armor - as armor don't save from injuries.

Q280 In what circumstances does the efficiency at shooting from turrets get reset? I was at 70% yesterday, then slept for 4 cycles or so, then I was down to 30% again (36 with lenses) My first 4 missed shots are just pure loss then?
On july 16, 2014
[6826491]

A280: Efficiency for any action like that (firing, repairing, or dismantling) drops back to baseline the instant you take another action that uses AP, including the conversion of AP to MP. If you were say, dismantling a shower, then you could make your attempt, sleep, and then try again in a few cycles without losing efficiency.

Similarly, if you had enough MP to use a turret, get back to a dorm and sleep, without spending a single AP on anything else, and then you get back to that turret later, your efficiency would be the same as when you left. (It's quite a hassle to pull that off, but this knowledge is better put to use for repairing or dismantling actions.)

Q297: when the alert shows 30+ hostile vessels and you can only see 17, does it mean those you can't see are all regular hunters? (and all other types are always visible in the top 17)
On july 20, 2014
Kyubey

A297 No, you will see at least 1 type of every hunter present, but there can be more special types in unseen part, if you see at least one.
But in my experience, in most of situations you see hunters in proportion. Like: 34 hunters came, you see 15 normal and 2 traxes. There will be very likely another 15 normal and 2 traxes in unseen part, maybe 3-4 traxes, but not all 17.
On july 20, 2014
[6826491]

A297: The "first spots" (the spots on the top right) are designed to have one of each enemy type present, even if you can't see the others. Those spots are the ones you must watch for. If you kill one of the special enemies in the top right, then another one will always take its spot (if there is one.)

From this, you can conclude that if you have 20+ hunters, and you can't see an Arack in the top right, then you can move the ship that cycle. By the same token, if you only want to kill Aracks/Trax, then focus your attacks on the top right; if they don't get replaced, there are none left of that type.
